			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Profile-Based Abstraction and Analysis of Attribute Grammar Evaluation</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AnthonyMSloane.html">Anthony M. Sloane</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_3">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_3</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2012s/paper05.html"><em>Domain-specific program profiling and its application to attribute grammars and term rewriting</em></a> (SLE 2012 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The paper analyzes properties of attribute-grammar evaluation (driven by profiling) to support understanding and optimization.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Profiling-based abstractions are used to reason about evaluation costs and performance bottlenecks.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Attribute grammars are the underlying language-definition formalism being studied and characterized.
</li></ul></li></ul>
